In this table the reader cannot fail to be struck with the close adherence of q to b until we get to the latter chapters of St. John ; there is not in the first three Gospels a single case of divergence, but they always change from magmfico to honorifico and back to magnifico together, while f diverges frequ‘ently into glorifico, and in Matt. ix. 8 has magmfico against the honorifico of b, q. The appearance of clarifico in b in the latter chapters of St. John, and not only in b but in f, whence it has crept in a few places into the Vulgate, is very puzzling3 for clari- ficoo, from its regular use in the African MSS. e, k, and in the quotations of African Fathers‚ would seem to be a distinctly African term ; q here agrees with a in reading honorzfico (glorifico, it may be noted, is not once found in q), and it may be possible that in these chapters the text of b has been slightly corrupted from an African source, while a and q have preselved the genuine European rendering. Another point worthy of notice is that in John xiii. 32 q inserts with f the initial clause et si deus honorificatus est in eo against a, ῤ, d (which omit it and go straight to et deus honorzficabz't eum, etc.); but though qagrees with s in the reading, it differs in the rendering, having honorzficatus instead of clarzficatus.
